Male":"Deceased","1127–1187":"1127–1187","1056–1109":"1056–1109","1056–1121":"1056–1121","1080":"1080","1091":"1091","1090":"1090","1121":"1121","1132":"1132","1187":"1187","1086":"1086","1182":"1182","about 1109":"about 1109","1127":"1127","1115":"1115","1146":"1146","1079":"1079","1056":"1056","1109":"1109","Ham-sur-Heure-Nalinnes, Arrondissement de Thuin, Province de Hainaut, Belgique":"Ham-sur-Heure-Nalinnes, Hainaut, Belgium","Ham, Somme, Picardie, France":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, France","Ham, Somme, Picardie, França":"Ham, Somme, Picardie, France","Tripoli, Ţarābulus, Libya":"Tripoli, Ţarābulus, Libya","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"HAM-DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Bjorn, Knute, Lars, Svein.","Norwegian: habitational name from numerous farmsteads, notably in western Norway, named Hamre, from the dative case of Old Norse <i>hamarr</i> ‘cliff, rock’. See   Hamar  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hamar","meanings":["Hungarian: nickname from the adjective <i>hamar</i> ‘fast’.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads named Hamar, from Old Norse <i>hamarr</i> ‘hammer’, denoting a hammer-shaped cliff or crag.","English (Shropshire and Lancashire): variant of   Hamer  ."]}]},{"name":"WALCOURT","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French Canadian: altered form of French   Delcourt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dalcour","meanings":["American French: variant of   Dalcourt  ."]},{"name":"Delcourt","meanings":["French (northern): shortened form of <b>Delacourt</b> (or <b>Delecourt</b>), a topographic name, with fused preposition <i>de</i> and definite article <i>la</i> ‘from the’, for someone ‘from the court, farmyard’ (see   Court   2), or a habitational name denoting someone from La Cour (see   Lacour  ). Compare   Dalcourt  ."]}]},{"name":"Gérard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. In the later Middle Ages this was a more common name than   Gerald  , with which it was sometimes confused. Nowadays it is less common, surviving mainly among Roman Catholics, in honour of the many saints of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Gerard  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Jerrard","meanings":["Rare variant spelling of   Gerard  , probably influenced by the form of the modern surname, if not a transferred use."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"dit","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Christopher ;  also of   Katherine   and its variants. In the medieval period it was a pet form of   Christian   and   Christiana ."],"variants":[{"name":"Christopher","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Khristophoros</i>, from <i>Khristos</i> ‘Christ’ + <i>pherein</i> ‘to bear’. This was popular among early Christians, conscious of the fact that they were metaphorically bearing Christ in their hearts. A later, over-literal interpretation of the name gave rise to the legend of a saint who actually bore the Christ-child over a stream; he is regarded as the patron of travellers. In England the name was uncommon in the Middle Ages, but became very popular in the 16th century, especially in parts of the North."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Variant of   Katherine ."]}]},{"name":"Le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Preux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Preuss  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Preuss","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Eckhard, Erwin, Gerda, Horst, Gunter, Ilse, Klaus, Lothar, Monika, Rainer.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Prussia (German <i>Preussen</i>), a former state of northern Germany, so called from the ethnic name of a Baltic people (see   Prus  ) displaced by the Germans during the 13th century, or an ethnic name for a member of this people."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gérard II dit Le Preux DE HAM-DE WALCOURT was born in 1080, in Ham, Somme, Picardie, France, his father, Gérard de Vermandois I de Heure Lord of Ham, was 25 and his mother, Marguerite Marie De Peronne, was 24. He had at least 2 sons with Blanche de Breteuil Dame de Breteuil. He died in 1132, in Tripoli, Ţarābulus, Libya, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1080–1132":"1080–1132","1086–Female":"1086–Surnud","1091–1146":"1091–1146","1090–1127":"1090–1127","1115–1182":"1115–1182","–Male":"Surnud","1127–1187":"1127–1187","1056–1109":"1056–